b'[<p><i><b>UFC Fight Night: Shogun vs. Henderson 2</b></i> (also known as <i><b>UFC Fight Night 38</b></i>) was a <a href="/wiki/Mixed_martial_arts" title="Mixed martial arts">mixed martial arts</a> event held on March 23, 2014, at the <a href="/wiki/Gin%C3%A1sio_N%C3%A9lio_Dias" title="Gin\xc3\xa1sio N\xc3\xa9lio Dias">Gin\xc3\xa1sio N\xc3\xa9lio Dias</a> in <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Natal,_Brazil" title="Natal, Brazil">Natal, Brazil</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-FNNatal_2-0"><a href="#cite_note-FNNatal-2">[2]</a></sup>\n</p>, <p>The event was headlined by the anticipated rematch between mixed martial arts legends <a href="/wiki/Maur%C3%ADcio_Rua" title="Maur\xc3\xadcio Rua">Maur\xc3\xadcio Rua</a> and <a href="/wiki/Dan_Henderson" title="Dan Henderson">Dan Henderson</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-FNNatal_2-1"><a href="#cite_note-FNNatal-2">[2]</a></sup> Henderson won their first encounter back in November 2011 at <a href="/wiki/UFC_139" title="UFC 139">UFC 139</a> via unanimous decision in a bout lauded by many MMA pundits as the <i>Fight of the Year</i> for 2011 and one of the best bouts in the history of the UFC.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-3"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-4"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup>\n</p>, <p>The co-main event featured a long-planned bout between <a href="/wiki/Cezar_Ferreira" title="Cezar Ferreira">Cezar Ferreira</a> and <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/C.B._Dollaway" title="C.B. Dollaway">C.B. Dollaway</a>. The two were originally scheduled to meet on May 18, 2013 at <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/UFC_on_FX_8" title="UFC on FX 8">UFC on FX 8</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-5"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> However, both Dollaway<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-6"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup>  and Ferreira<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-7"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> had been forced from the bout due to injury.\n</p>, <p><a href="/wiki/Gleison_Tibau" title="Gleison Tibau">Gleison Tibau</a> was expected to face <a href="/wiki/Mairbek_Taisumov" title="Mairbek Taisumov">Mairbek Taisumov</a> at the event.  However, Tibau pulled out of the bout citing injury and was replaced by <a href="/wiki/Michel_Prazeres" title="Michel Prazeres">Michel Prazeres</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TibauOut_8-0"><a href="#cite_note-TibauOut-8">[8]</a></sup>\n</p>, <p><a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Diego_Brandao" title="Diego Brandao">Diego Brandao</a> was expected to face Will Chope at the event and both men weighed in successfully on March 22 for the fight.  However, after the weigh ins, the bout was cancelled when documents were released that showed Chope assaulted and threatened his ex-wife, which led to jail time and a dishonorable discharge from the U.S. Air Force\n</p>, <p>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-9"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup>\n</p>, <p><a href="/wiki/Ronny_Markes" title="Ronny Markes">Ronny Markes</a> missed the Middleweight limit of 186\xc2\xa0lbs. for his bout with <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Thiago_de_Lima_Santos" title="Thiago de Lima Santos">Thiago Santos</a>. As a result, he was fined 20% of his purse and the bout was changed to a catchweight of 190\xc2\xa0lbs.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-10"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup>\n</p>, <p>UFN 38 saw an average of 936,000 viewers with a peak of 1.25 million during the main event.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-11"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup>\n</p>, <p><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-14"><a href="#cite_note-14">[12]</a></sup>\n</p>, <p>The following fighters were awarded $50,000 bonuses:<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-15"><a href="#cite_note-15">[13]</a></sup>\n</p>]'